cwn_entry.cwn_what:
I have got another solution to possibly resolve this problem: I've developed an embedded O'Caml toplevel which integrates the runtime and the compiler of O'Caml. Actually, it's a dynamic linked library (in C) builds using the "ouput-obj" option; i have solved the problem of the symbole table thanks to a modification of the compiler and the runtime.
you can download the patch at this url: http://www.pps.jussieu.fr/~capel/eng/toplevel/toplevel.html
you will find also an O'Caml plugin for Excel and Netscape in this page.
Just an example to show you how it works (in C): (you can also use the directives #use and #load)
toplevel_init(argv);
toplevel_exec("let rec ack m n = match m,n with 0,n -> n+1 | m,0 -> ack (m-1) 1 | m,n -> (ack (m-1) ack m (n-1))");
val = toplevel_exec("ack 3 2;;"); res = 1+Long_val(val);
printf ("1+ack(3,2)=%dn", res);
I hope it will help you.
